# Frontend Workflow

When working under `frontend/`, use a lighter process than backend or core logic. This overrides the small-step and full-diff review expectations in `collaborative-workflow.mdc` for frontend files only.

## Larger chunks are fine

- Implement related UI changes together (e.g. a page, its components, and styles in one pass).
- Do not split every component or style tweak into a separate approval step unless the user asks.
- Still get approval before large refactors or changes that touch routing, shared layout, or API wiring — but routine UI work can move faster.

## Lighter review format

After frontend changes, summarize in plain language what was done and why. Do **not** walk through every file line by line.

Include only **2–4 short code highlights** — the parts that matter most (new component structure, key state/hooks, notable layout or styling). Skip boilerplate, imports, and obvious markup.

**Good:**
> Added a model card grid on Discover. Cards show name, size, and a load button; clicking load calls the existing API hook. Grid is responsive with `auto-fill` columns.

```tsx
// DiscoverPage — card grid + load handler
{models.map((m) => (
  <ModelCard key={m.id} model={m} onLoad={() => loadModel(m.id)} />
))}
```

**Avoid:** pasting full files, exhaustive before/after for every touched file, or step-by-step narration of CSS utilities and JSX structure.

## What stays the same

- Match existing frontend style and patterns.
- Minimal scope — no unrelated drive-by edits outside the task.
- Do not commit or push unless the user explicitly asks.
